The increased incidence of pertussis has triggered a wide-ranging expert debate on the effectiveness of current pertussis prevention strategies. According to expert considerations, the most likely causes for the increased pertussis morbidity rates (Figure 1) include:
Evolution of B. pertussis under selective pressure exerted by vaccines, particularly aP vaccines [41];
Waning of the immunity conferred by vaccination (faster in the case of aP vaccines) [42,43,44];
B. pertussis transmission by asymptomatic carriers [45];
Improvements in pertussis surveillance and in diagnostic methods.
